       }
    }
    
Let&#39;s assume compiler allows the subclass method to be weaker access privileges.

Below is how **main** method will be checked at compilation :
1. Access Modifiers are checked at compile time. (check statically).
2. In main method compiler will see superClassVariable is of type Superclass.
3. Compiler **can&#39;t** determine the object type (Subclass) during compilation.
4. So Compiler will check Superclass foo() method for access modifier.
5. Method foo in Superclass is having default access modifier so it can be accessed 
   in Main class. The Compiler will allow this Main class code.

But as we know it is Voilation of access privileges. 
foo() method for Subclass is private.
We created Subclass object in Main class.
Called private foo() method of Subclass object from Main class.

So to avoid issues/bug during **overriding**, and ensure that access privileges are not violated compiler forces to assign stronger or same access privileges to overriding method

