Here&#39;s a contrived version.  You will need to figure out how to apply it to your requirements. Once it find&#39;s `&quot;C&quot;` it will not repeat.  It works by using the default to reset the `tryAgain`  flag to `true`. Once the `do/while` loop restarts, the flag is immediately set to false assuming a match will be found.  Using `toUpperCase` negates the need for multiple strings for the same type.
```
boolean tryAgain;
String[] vals = {&quot;a&quot;,&quot;B&quot;,&quot;c&quot;,&quot;D&quot;};
int i = 0;
String result;
do {
    tryAgain = false;
    result = switch (vals[i++].toUpperCase()) {
        case &quot;C&quot; -&gt; &quot;Found C&quot;;
        case &quot;D&quot; -&gt; &quot;Found D&quot;;

        default -&gt; {
            tryAgain = true;
            yield &quot;&quot;;
        }
    };

} while (tryAgain);
System.out.println(result);
```
prints
```
Found C
```
The above could also be done as follows.  No default required here. 
```
String result = &quot;&quot;;
outer:
for (String val : vals) {
     switch(val.toUpperCase()) {
        case &quot;C&quot; -&gt; {
                       result =&quot;Found C&quot;;
                       break outer;
        }
        
        case &quot;D&quot; -&gt; { 
                      result = &quot;Found D&quot;;
                      break outer;
        }
    };
}
System.out.println(result);
```
And lastly another using `continue` as the default to skip over the latter print and break statements when nothing is found.
```

String result = &quot;&quot;;

for (String val : vals) {
    switch(val.toUpperCase()) {
        case &quot;C&quot; -&gt; result = &quot;Found C&quot;;

        case &quot;D&quot; -&gt; result = &quot;Found D&quot;;

        default -&gt; {
            continue;
        }
    }
    System.out.println(result);
    break;
}
```

